article.headline: LeBron scores 32 and has 10 assists
article.linkText: Cavs make it two in a row on the road
article.story:
CHICAGO (AP) -- LeBron James did the No. 23 proud in his idol's house. With Michael Jordan watching from a skybox, James scored a game-high 32 points and had a career-high 10 assists Saturday night to lead the Cleveland Cavaliers to their second straight road win, a 95-87 victory over the Chicago Bulls. "I saw him before the game," James said. "But I just wanted to play my game. I played a good game, I helped my team." Helped the Cavaliers? More like carried them. He scored Cleveland's last 14 points, played some nasty defense and had a line veteran players would envy. He was 11-of-22 from the floor and 10-of-12 from the line, and he had six rebounds, two steals and two blocks while turning the ball over four times. It was an effort that was, well, Jordanesque. "If you knock it all back to the basics of the game, I think you would be hard-pressed to find too many guys in the league that can do those things as well as he can," Bulls coach Scott Skiles said. He knows how to ruin a good party, too. This was like old home night at the United Center, with Jordan kicking back in a suite with former teammates Charles Oakley and Will Perdue, and Jay Williams at his first game since the devastating June motorcycle accident that's threatened his career. But James came in and made himself right at home. The Bulls led 71-65 with 30 seconds left in the third quarter, but Cleveland went on a 13-2 run. Chicago went almost six minutes without scoring a field goal. And when the Bulls finally did make a run, James stopped them in their tracks, ripping off 10 points in the last two minutes. The Bulls had pulled within 85-82 on Jerome Williams' layup with 2:25 to play. But James responded with a 16-foot jumper. On Cleveland's next possession, he let fly with a 19-foot jumper that drew a gasp from the crowd. He then sealed the victory with six free throws. "What can you say? He's big-time now," Cleveland coach Paul Silas said. "He hit some big shots, got big rebounds and played defense. We need it, and he provides it for us. I think it's all really starting to come for him. He handles the hype and the pressure extremely well. "Let's just say `He's got it," Silas said. Indeed, it's been a big weekend for James. He scored 36 points Friday night, helping Cleveland break a 34-game road losing streak that was tied for second-longest in NBA history. His signature shoe went on sale early Saturday -- he stopped by Niketown before the game to check it out -- and then got to play in Jordan's house. In front of His Airness, no less. "That's my idol, always will be. This is his house, always will be," James said before the game. "But I'm going to go out and just play my game. I'm not trying to praise anybody but my teammates and my coaches." Jordan stopped by before the game to say hello, though James wouldn't say what they talked about. "He didn't tell me nothing," James said, laughing. "You all don't need to know everything I do." Jordan declined to comment after the game, but he had to like what he saw in the player many believe is his heir apparent. James certainly doesn't play like an 18-year-old, or a rookie. He could have had even more points, but he chose to get his teammates involved early. By the end of the first quarter, he had six assists. "I can turn it on and off at any time," James said. "Some of my teammates maybe can't do that, so I try to get them into the game so I can have them late." And when James turns it on, he's dazzling. He scored on a fast-break layup even though he was falling backward, and he had the crowd roaring when he scored on a one-handed slam over three defenders. He had some monstrous slams that would have been worth bonus points in a dunk contest, and his defense frustrated Jamal Crawford and Kirk Hinrich. Crawford finished with 16 points but was just 7-for-27 while Hinrich had 10 on 4-of-12 shooting. "Every night I go out," James said, "I'm just trying to help my team win the best way I can."

Game notes
Asked before the game if he'd like to have Jordan back in a Bulls uniform, Skiles joked, "Not at the age he is now." After a pause he said, "Maybe I better rethink that." ... It was the Bulls' fifth sellout of the season. They're 1-4 in sellouts. ... Chicago is 0-2 this season when Jordan attends a game. ... It was the first time Cleveland won consecutive road games since Feb. 16-22, 2002. The Cavaliers were 3-38 on the road last season.
